Source: Union Leader
<http://www.theunionleader.com/articles_showa.html?article=59667>

New EEE cases suspected in Concord, Manchester
----------------------
2 new suspected cases of Eastern equine encephalitis were announced
yesterday by the state Department of Health and Human Services, bringing to
4 the number of human cases of the potentially-deadly mosquito-borne virus
in New Hampshire.
2 men, one from Manchester and the other from Concord, were hospitalized
over the weekend, said John A. Stephen, DHHS commissioner.
He said that although the Manchester man was released late yesterday
afternoon, the DHHS still considers both cases �preliminary positive,�
pending lab results due Friday.
Stephen announced the 2 additional cases yesterday afternoon � a day after
laboratory tests confirmed that a Londonderry woman and a 4-year-old
Goffstown boy were infected with EEE, a rare brain-inflaming disease known
to be fatal in severe cases, killing about 1/3 of those afflicted,
according to the Centers for Disease Control.
The 2 confirmed cases are the first human cases contracted in New Hampshire.
According to the CDC, there have been a total of 200 confirmed cases in the
U.S. since 1964, with an average of 4 confirmed cases each year nationally.
6 cases of Eastern equine encephalitis were reported nationwide in 2004 --
4 of them occurred in Massachusetts, with 3 of them resulting in death.
�Yes, it is unusual for our state to be looking at 4 possible cases in one
year,� Stephen said. �Obviously, we�ve been tracking cases for a number of
years. But it�s not unusual if you consider last year there were 4 cases
confirmed in Massachusetts.�
�If anything, I would say it�s unexpected, in terms of the New England
region,� Stephen said.
In light of trends in New Hampshire over the last few years involving West
Nile Virus and EEE, the DHHS has adopted a consistent mantra for the public
at large.
�Prevention, prevention prevention. We know in 100 percent of cases,
prevention works,� Stephen said. �We want to make sure the public gets that
message, and is aware that it�s a serious disease.�
Symptoms of the disease range from a mild flu to lethargy, mental confusion
and coma. The public should err on the side of caution when seeking
treatment for flu-like illness, officials said.
Using insect repellent containing DEET, wearing protective clothing and
eliminating standing water where mosquitoes can breed are the best way to
avoid infection, Stephen said.
EEE tends to occur in cycles, with transmission most often detected in
swampy, lower-populated areas along the Eastern Seaboard. States with the
most confirmed cases historically have been Massachusetts, New Jersey,
Florida and Georgia -- where one confirmed EEE death was reported in early
August [2005] by the Georgia health department.
However, with possible outbreaks in urban settings the health department is
recommending both Manchester and Concord pursue spraying to kill adult
mosquitoes.
In Manchester, the plan to spray mosquito-killing insecticide in city parks
may be delayed until mid-week, said Fred Rusczek, the city�s public health
director.
�We have everything in place to spray, but before we spray we have to give
48 hours� notification to the (state) Pesticide Control Board, which we
will do Monday,� Rusczek said.
Weather is another limiting factor.
Rusczek said rain is forecast for early in the week, which could put the
spraying off until Thursday or Friday. The chemical permethrin is dispersed
as a mist in the evening hours. It kills adult mosquitoes on contact, but
is ineffective in rainy or windy conditions.
Spraying will be done only in the city�s parks and playgrounds.
�Our goal is to kill the adult biting mosquitoes in areas where there are
large numbers of people congregating � the youth sport fields and some of
the heavier-use parks -- as a way of reducing the risk by reducing the
exposure to mosquitoes that potentially carry either EEE or West Nile
Virus,� Rusczek said.
3 weeks ago, Concord health officer Eugene Blake said the city had applied
for and was waiting to receive a spraying permit.
While EEE in humans is still considered rare, deputy state epidemiologist
Dr. Elizabeth Talbot said yesterday that, at this stage in the
investigation, all people who have outdoor exposure to mosquitoes in the
Manchester and Concord areas are at risk.
�You don�t need to live on a swamp,� Talbot said. �And at the same time,
we�re trying to balance the message by saying there�s no reason for panic.
We don�t expect it to become an outbreak of epidemic proportions.�
Health officials said based on previous activity, mosquitoes will likely
remain active through September -- which means the potential for more
confirmed human cases.
�We will not be surprised to see additional human cases in the next 4
weeks,� Talbot said. �This is an emerging infection in New Hampshire. Last
year we had bird, horse and mosquitoes with triple-E for the first time.
Humans and horses are incidental hosts.�
She said it�s important for the public to understand that EEE within the
horse population doesn�t increase the risk for human contraction of the
disease.
�Triple E in horses has heightened our awareness of the existence of
triple-E, but it in no way contributes to human infection,� Talbot said. �A
widespread equine vaccine campaign would not likely impact the incidence of
human disease.�
[Byline: Carol Robidoux]
