[2]
Date: 27 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Laconia Citizen, NH [edited]
<http://www.citizen.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20050826/CITIZEN0106/108260063/-1/CITIZEN>

State health officials have detected a dead bird in the city that has been
confirmed to have been infected with eastern equine encephalitis (EEE), and
there is concern that the disease is spreading.
A press release from the Department of Health and Human Services indicates
that a deceased bird in Franklin and 2 others in Canterbury and Hooksett
have tested positively for the disease at the state public health laboratory.
"Obviously, we are concerned, because we are now seeing that this virus is
spreading over a larger geographic area," said Health and Human Service
Commissioner John Stephen.
According to the Health and Human Service website, eastern equine
encephalitis is a rare but serious viral disease -- that is also caused by
a virus transmitted by the bite of an infected mosquito -- with more severe
symptoms than for West Nile virus.
EEE is an arbovirus -- short for arthropod-borne -- meaning it is spread by
insects. Birds are the source of infection for mosquitoes, which can
sometimes transmit the infection to horses, other animals, and, in rare
cases, to humans.
This year [2005], the state has seen 2 suspected cases of EEE in humans,
and the state anticipates confirmation of samples of these individuals by
today [27 Aug 2005].
Infection can cause a range of illnesses. Most people have no symptoms;
others get only a mild flu-like illness with fever, headache, and sore
throat. For people with infection of the central nervous system, a sudden
high fever (103 to 106 degrees), severe headache, and stiff neck can be
followed quickly by seizures and coma. About 1/3rd of these patients die
from the disease.
Officials remain steadfast that the best way to react to the spread of the
disease is prevention.
"Eastern equine [encephalitis] is preventable if people take common sense
prevention measures. I hope everyone takes appropriate actions, including
removing standing water, wearing long sleeves and pants in high mosquito
areas and using effective mosquito repellant," said Stephen.
The Department of Health and Human Services has listed prevention methods
for stopping mosquito-borne illnesses on its website at
<http://www.dhhs.nh.go>. Information can also be found on their toll-free
hotline for West Nile Virus available from 8 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. at
1-866-273-6453.
The department is currently testing mosquitoes from around the state for
both EEE and West Nile virus and is also working with medical providers and
local health officials so they can identify symptoms early.
[Byline: Geoff Cunningham Jr. ]
--
