<promed@promedmail.org>
[Birds are usually sentinels for this disease. Health departments have
sometimes used chickens to monitor for this disease. Emus are very
sensitive to the disease. If birds are being found with this disease, horse
owners are advised to vaccinate. In addition to vaccination, horse owners
should use a recommended equine spray to help control flies and mosquitoes
on the animals.
Vaccines for horses are usually in combination: West Nile virus, western
equine encephalitis, eastern equine encephalitis and Venezuelan equine
encephalitis. There are also combination vaccines that do not have the
Venezuelan portion. - Mod.TG]
[EEE virus is closely related to Western and Venezuelan equine encephalitis
viruses belonging to the family _Togaviridae_, genus _Alphavirus_. The EEE
transmission cycle involves mainly birds and mosquitoes. EEE virus can be
transmitted to humans, an innocent host, by an infected mosquito. Although
EEE human cases are relatively rare (4 cases per year, mainly in the
eastern half of the US), if it occurs, it can result in neurological
illness and even death (a case fatality rate of 35 percent, which is
generally more severe than West Nile virus infection). EEE virus can infect
several mosquito species. Among them, _Culiseta melanura_ is the most
significant vector. A dead bird, a natural sentinel animal, has been
proven to have been infected with EEE virus. This means that EEE virus
infection is active in the region. - Mod.RY]
